David Brin touched on this "fad" in his novel The Uplift War. Humans have uplifted "chims" into full sapience, but the process still has to be managed and has many problems to fix and adjust. This results in a counter-culture among the chim population, since uncontrolled breeding can't be allowed for genetically inferior individuals. (NOT entirely a human rule; it's galactic law and policy for the betterment of all species)

Anyway. Among this working-class of genetic rejects who experience a number of various genetic flaws that make life difficult, many such disadvantaged turn to crime and other marginally legal activities. What do they have to lose? They aren't allowed to have children of their own, and some are considered so flawed that they are barred from having access to children at all. In this setting, also, they are on a backwater planet far removed from more advanced and dense civilization

Among some of these it became fashionable to shave and sculpt their facial hair. In some ways it was to mimic human fashion, but in other ways it was just an expression of rebellion and to stand out. Much like a pimp wearing expensive & flashy clothes to advertise their lifestyle. In chim society, it was considered a shocking effect, and looked down upon as something lowlifes do. I guess similar to how humans who get into extreme body mod with tattoos and extreme piercings and such in our world. Some just go too far, others find an aesthetic balance that satisfies them and most other people accept it, even admire it.

So, certain facial hair designs/mods might be more shocking to other humans and the anthros barely notice. Dyed fur & dyed patterns might create more of an interest/fashion statement.

>TwoKinds? Is it /hmofa/ enough?
Yes.

"Should" you read it? Hard to say. Because this >>38585718 is quite true. But, it does have more redeeming features than that. Keep in mind that Tom started that story 15 years ago, the first few chapters have pretty primitive art and really bad writing. He created numerous gigantic plot holes because he never thought & mapped the story out until much later.

On the other hand, the art gets better and eventually becomes some of the best available for any comic/artist. Some folks may not enjoy his style, but his mastery of technique these days is undeniable. Any artist would be glad to accomplish what he has, even if they would rather apply that talent to a different style.

The writing has improved, but it's a clusterfuck of entangled ideas and stories. And updates are fairly slow these days because he does so much other art (which brings him in some very serious bank from Patreon, among other sources, so it's understandable that he's putting money in the bank). And he's working on other projects which, quite frankly, are suffering from his not-very-good writing style, lame pacing, and inability to learn from his other writing mistakes.

All that said, the world is rich. Incredibly rich. You get invested in it for the imagination & possibilities of the world, despite its flaws. Some characters different people can get invested in, but I don't find any of them particularly deep. That's been the greatest disappointment for me. I don't give much a fuck about the main characters, and the interesting side characters will never carry their own storyline.
